VYoung and laudable
p3
sVnews
p4
VThe Vijayawada Music Academy arranged a violin solo concert by Vinjamuri Kamalakiran at Sri Sivaramakrishna Kshetram. To the surprise of the audience, a young boy of eight walked on to the stage and mesmerised one and all with his violin.Kamalakiran is the son of Vinjamuri Subhash, a reputed violinist who accompanied many vidwans in their U.S. concerts. Throughout the concert, Kiran showed perfectsrutialignment,layaprecision and excellent grasp of raga bhavas. He was trained by his father. The boy began the concert withSaranga varnamandVatapi Ganapathim Bhajehamin Hamsadhvani, which concluded with goodkalpana swaras.Next cameVasudevayaniin Kalyani. Thekeertanawas preceded by good delineation of the raga. Following thisBhavanutain Mohana,Nada Tanum Anisamin Chttaranjani andPalukavemi NaDaivamawere played in quick succession.Kamalakiran took up Dikshitar&#8217;s majestic composition in Dwijavanthi,Akhilandeswarifor the main item of the concert. This selection itself confirmed the youngster&#8217;s mastery over the raga. The difficult raga was presented well. He had excellent rhythmic support from K. Sai Giridhar on the mridangam and S. Hanumanta Rao on the ghatam. At the end ofAkhilandesweari, Giridhar and Hanumanta Rao combined well to present an engagingtani.During the function that followed Manda Krishna Mohan, vocal vidwan and a staffer of the Government College of Music and Dance and Natyacharya K. Ajay Kumar, a well known exponent of Kuchipudi, were felicitated by the Vijayawada Music Academy for their recent successful U.S. tour as part of the Kuchipudi festival conducted by the Sililcon Andhra of California.
